CloudTrail?

CloudTrail stores API call logs. That's its primary job.

complete audit history of every API action across your AWS accounts — who did what, when, from where, on which resource.

CloudTrail works at individual account level AND organization level.

What it captures:

Who did it?     → IAM user / role / service
What did it?    → API action (e.g. ec2:TerminateInstance)
When?           → Timestamp
Where from?     → IP address, region
On what?        → Resource ARN
Result?         → Success or error

Organization Trail (recommended):

Management Account
 └── One Org CloudTrail trail
      ├── Dev Account    ✅ auto covered
      ├── Staging Account ✅ auto covered
      ├── Prod Account   ✅ auto covered
      ├── Security Account ✅ auto covered
      └── Shared Services ✅ auto covered
           └── All logs → centralized S3 (Log Archive Account)

What it stores:

Every API call → captured as an Event → stored as JSON log file

Everything in AWS is an API call under the hood:

You click "Launch EC2 instance" in console
        │
        ▼
Console calls → ec2:RunInstances API
        │
        ▼
CloudTrail logs it

Real examples by service:

What you did                     | API call logged
---------------------------------|------------------------------
Created S3 bucket                | s3:CreateBucket
Deleted EC2 instance             | ec2:TerminateInstances
Changed IAM policy               | iam:PutUserPolicy
Disabled CloudTrail              | cloudtrail:StopLogging
Assumed IAM role                 | sts:AssumeRole
Created EKS cluster              | eks:CreateCluster
Pushed to ECR                    | ecr:PutImage
Applied Terraform                | multiple API calls

Where it stores:

CloudTrail
 ├── S3 Bucket          → long term storage (primary)
 ├── CloudWatch Logs    → real time search & alerts
 └── EventBridge        → trigger automated actions

